five sample summaries

[1]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 
[2] The speaker said that in order to solve the problems people face, we need to change our short-termism thinking and fundamentally rethink things along a longpath. First generatinel thinking. This mindset is a way of looking for solutions across generations. People can look back in history to learn from the ideas of ancient philosophers, but at the same time, they must consider how their current actions will affect the children who will be responsible for the next generation. Second,  futures thinking. This means that we can't just think about technology. Instead of trying to apply technology as a quick fix, we need to look at things from a different perspective. Finally,  telos thinking. It means ultimate aim and ultimate purpose. And the important thing is to what end? When the current problems are solved, we need to predict what will happen next, hundreds of years into the future. The future is a verb, not a noun. We need to take it into our own hands and change it.                                                                                                     
[3] This speaker argues that modern society suffers from short termism focusing on immediate goals at the expense of long term future planning. To counter this, the speaker proposes three models of thinking: transgenerational, futures, and telos to expand how we make decisions affecting future generations. HIs message is that planning for the very long term helps address large, complex global challenges and creates a more responsible legacy.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       
[4] Ari Wallach says that our society has a big problem called short-termism. He explains that many leaders today only think about the next few months instead of the distant future. He calls their quick fixes sandbag strategies, He says these temporary solutions might work for a short time, but they do not solve the real causes of big problems. To change our future, he suggests a new practice called  Longpath. This practice has three main parts. First, he talks about Transgenerational Thinking. He says we should think beyond our own lives and consider how our actions today will affect many generations later. Second, he mentions Futures Thinking. He explains that we should imagine many different possible futures, not just focus on new technology. Finally, he talks about Telos Thinking. He says we must ask, To what end? to find our ultimate goal for the next 100 years.                                                                                                                                                                                                             
[5] As a world where the next generation grows up,we desire a society that prioritizes long-term perspectives over short-term gains or fears,making decisions based on responsibility toward future generations.The three ways are transgenerational thinking and future thinking and telos thinking.Technology should not only serve efficiency but also contribute to human well-being,dignity,and improvements in education and healthcare.Furthermore,by fostering awareness of the connections between past,present,and future,people are encouraged to act responsibly toward the environment and others,paving the way for a hopeful,sustainable,and inclusive society. In addition, such a society would encourage cooperation rather than competition and value shared responsibility over individual success. Education would emphasize empathy, critical thinking, and long-term impact, helping people understand how their actions shape the future. By embedding these values into institutions and everyday life, societies can better prepare future generations to face global challenges with resilience and hope.

Opinions

five sample opinions

[1] I have never thought of it, but this TED talk made me realise that I sometimes may be thinking in the short term. For example, when I buy clothes, I may be planning in the short term. I only think I will wear it this year or on my next vacation, and don t think whether I will wear the clothes next year. Buying clothes only for the short term is not good for the environment. I may have to plan what food to buy in the long term. However, I think there are parts that I am planning for the long term. For example, I quit my part time job and started to go on a long term internship. This is because I wanted to learn how to work at a company while I am a student. In my long term plan, I am thinking this experience will help me when I start working full time, and will be able to get up to speed quickly and advance my career.
[2] Recently, I realized that I tend to think only about the next few days or at most the next month. However, considering that humans may live for 70 to 90 years, if each of us focuses only on the present, major global issues will never be resolved and may eventually lead to consequences that threaten humanity itself. Through this story, I came to feel that I want to think more seriously about what we can do, within our own time and capacity, to address larger, long-term challenges.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         
[3] When people think about long term problems such as war or infection, they often say that we should not pass on the problems to the next generation. However, the TED speaker predicted that long term problems can continue even if generation changes. Also, he claimed that people should think about long term problems beyond generations. It is very innovative. People will not prevent long term problems completely in the future. However, they can obtain knowledge or technology from the experiences. They should pass on these things to the next generations.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  
[4]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              
[5] I was a little confused about the term of futuring but I thought it amazing what he said about treating future as a verb. I feel like if you are focusing on a benefit right in front of you, you will always mess up. I think that is how it works. As the power point showed, there were big accidents and people died because of it. That makes me think that we should think the long way. In my case, I sometimes go shopping even if I am broke. That is a short-termrism. I have to change my mind set first.
